<section class="prose">
  <h1>The openness charter</h1>
  <p class="updated">If we're asking for your family's group chat, you get to see how the sausage is made.</p>

  <p>
    Years ago, a small company called
    <a href="https://baremetrics.com/open-startup">Baremetrics</a> did
    something unusual: it put its revenue dashboard on the public internet,
    and called it Open Startup. It proved a business could be honest about
    its numbers and live.
  </p>
  <p>
    We're going further, for a simple reason: Eleven is built to become a
    <a href="/story/">co-operative</a>, and a co-op's books belong to its
    members. So openness isn't a marketing gesture we might quietly retire —
    it's the destination. Here's what we commit to, and where each piece
    stands.
  </p>

  <ol class="charter">
    <li>
      <h3>Live service status <span class="state live">Live</span></h3>
      <p>
        <a href="https://status.elevenmessenger.com">status.elevenmessenger.com</a>
        shows the health of the whole fleet, updated continuously — capacity,
        services, even which software versions are running. Aggregates only:
        it can't leak anything about an individual space, because the system
        doesn't give us that detail to leak.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Open carbon accounting <span class="state live">Live</span></h3>
      <p>
        What Eleven costs the planet, measured from the live fleet and
        published with the working shown — see
        <a href="/planet/">the planet page</a>. We re-measure as we grow;
        the numbers are only worth having if they stay honest.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>No dark patterns <span class="state live">Live</span></h3>
      <p>
        No streaks, no engagement metrics, no guilt mechanics, no growth
        hacks. This one is structural: Eleven has no analytics, so we
        couldn't A/B-test you into staying longer even if we wanted to.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Open finances <span class="state">Building</span></h3>
      <p>
        Revenue, costs, and what we pay ourselves, published as public
        dashboards. Payments only just switched on and the numbers are
        currently tiny — we'll publish them anyway, and keep publishing them
        when they're interesting.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Open unit economics <span class="state">Building</span></h3>
      <p>
        Further than dashboards: we'll show what a &euro;5-a-year space
        actually costs us to run, and where the rest goes. If a plan's
        margin is enormous, you'll be able to see that it's enormous — and
        watch it fund the free tier.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Open scale <span class="state">Building</span></h3>
      <p>
        How many spaces and how many members, in aggregate. Never anything
        about an individual space — we couldn't if we tried, and that's
        <a href="/security/">the point</a>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Open code <span class="state">Beta</span></h3>
      <p>
        The code that guards your messages isn't a black box: it ships to
        your browser readable, exactly as written, so anyone can check that
        what <a href="/security/">the security page</a> says is what the
        code does. Releases are public, and opening up fully is part of the
        road to the co-op.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h3>Open governance <span class="state">The destination</span></h3>
      <p>
        The co-operative: member ownership, open books as a legal duty
        rather than a promise, and no exit — nobody to sell you to, ever.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The one boundary</h2>
  <p>
    Our openness stops exactly where your privacy starts. Every number we
    publish is an aggregate across the fleet. Eleven is engineered so that
    the detailed version — who you are, who you talk to, what you said —
    doesn't exist on our side at all.
  </p>

  <h2>Hold us to it</h2>
  <p>
    This page is the commitment. If a piece marked &ldquo;building&rdquo;
    seems to be taking suspiciously long, ask us about it:
    <a href="mailto:team@elevenmessenger.com">team@elevenmessenger.com</a>.
  </p>
</section>
